Machine Learning - Personal Loan Campaign¶

Problem Statement¶

  1. To predict whether a liability customer will buy personal loans
  2. To understand which customer attributes are most significant in driving purchases
  3. To identify which segment of customers to target more.

Data Dictionary¶

  1. ID: Customer ID
  2. Age: Customer’s age in completed years
  3. Experience: # years of professional experience
  4. Income: Annual income of the customer (in thousand dollars)
  5. ZIP Code: Home Address ZIP code.
  6. Family: The family size of the customer
  7. CCAvg: Average spending on credit cards per month (in thousand dollars)
  8. Education: Education Level. 1: Undergrad; 2: Graduate;3: Advanced/Professional
  9. Mortgage: Value of house mortgage if any. (in thousand dollars)
  10. Personal_Loan: Did this customer accept the personal loan offered in the last campaign?
  11. Securities_Account: Does the customer have a securities account with the bank?
  12. CD_Account: Does the customer have a certificate of deposit (CD) account with the bank?
  13. Online: Do customers use Internet banking facilities?
  14. CreditCard: Does the customer use a credit card issued by any other Bank (excluding All Life Bank)?

Overview of the observations :¶

  1. The data has 5000 rows and 14 columns / features with no NULL and DUPLICATED values.
  2. All the columns are of integer data type except the CCAvg column.
  3. The Age of the customers is normally distrbuted as follows : Average age = ~45, Minimum Age = 23 and maximum age = 67.
  4. Negative value in Experience needs to be evaluated.
  5. The minimum Income is ~ 46 thousand dollars, maximum income is ~ 224 thousand dollars and average income is ~ 64 thousand dollars which maybe suggest a skewness in data possibly right skewed.
  6. The minimum Family size = 1, maximum family size = 4 and average family size = 2 - Dataset seems uniformly distributed and can be treated as a categorical variable as it holds only 4 values.
  7. The minimum CCAvg is 0 USD (which can be reflecting customers who do not own credit cards), maximum CCAvg is ~1.9 thousand dollars and average is ~ 10 thousand dollars - Dataset seems right skewed.
  8. The Education is a categorical variable where 1: Undergrad, 2: Graduate, 3: Advanced/Professional.
  9. Mortgage column seems right skewed.
  10. The Personal_Loan is a categorical variable where 1: customer accepted the personal loan offered in the last campaign and 0:customer didnot accept
  11. The Securities_Account is a categorical variable where 1: customer has Securities_Account 0:customer does not have Securities_Account
  12. The CD_Account is a categorical variable where 1: customer has CD_Account 0:customer does not have CD_Account
  13. The Online is a categorical variable where 1: customer uses online banking 0:customer does use online banking
  14. The CreditCard is a categorical variable where 1: customer use a credit card issued by any other Bank 0:customer does not use a credit card issued by any other Bank

#Define a function to plot the boxplot and histogram for all numerical variables

def histogram_boxplot(data, feature, figsize=(15, 10),kde=True):
    fig, (axis_box, axis_hist) = plt.subplots(nrows=2,sharex=True,gridspec_kw={"height_ratios": (0.25, 0.75)},figsize=figsize)  
    sns.set_palette("pastel")
    # creating the 2 subplots
    sns.boxplot(data=data, x=feature, ax=axis_box, showmeans=True)  
    sns.histplot(data=data, x=feature, ax=axis_hist, kde=kde)

#Labelled Bar plots for Categorical columns 

def labelled_barplot(data, feature):
    
    # Count the occurrences of each unique value in the feature
    count_data = data[feature].value_counts().reset_index()
    count_data.columns = ['Feature', 'Count']

    # Calculate the percentage of each count
    total_count = count_data['Count'].sum()
    count_data['Percentage'] = (count_data['Count'] / total_count) * 100

    # Create the bar plot
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
    sns.barplot(x='Feature', y='Count', data=count_data)

    # Adding percentages on the bars
    for index, row in count_data.iterrows():
        plt.text(row.name, row.Count, f"{row.Percentage:.1f}%", color='black', ha="center")

    plt.title(f"Distribution of {feature}")
    plt.xlabel(f"{feature}")
    plt.ylabel('Count')
    plt.show()

def stacked_bar_plot(data,x_var,target):
    pd.crosstab(data[x_var], data[target]).plot(kind='bar', stacked=True)

# defining a function to compute different metrics to check performance of a classification model built using sklearn

def model_performance_dt(model, predictors, target):

    # predicting using the independent variables
    predictions = model.predict(predictors)
    
    #Calculating the performance mtrics
    accuracy = accuracy_score(target, predictions)
    recall = recall_score(target, predictions)
    precision = precision_score(target, predictions)
    f1 = f1_score(target, predictions)

    # creating a dataframe of metrics
    performance_metrics_df = pd.DataFrame({"Accuracy": accuracy, "Recall": recall, "Precision": precision, "F1": f1},index=[0])

    return performance_metrics_df
In [49]:
# Compute the confusion matrix 

def confusion_matrix_dt(model, predictors, target):
    y_pred = model.predict(predictors)
    cm = confusion_matrix(target, y_pred)
    labels = np.asarray(
        [
            ["{0:0.0f}".format(item) + "\n{0:.2%}".format(item / cm.flatten().sum())]
            for item in cm.flatten()
        ]
    ).reshape(2, 2)

    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 4))
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=labels, fmt="")
    plt.ylabel("True label")
    plt.xlabel("Predicted label")
In [50]:
# Plot the feature importances graph for each model 

def feature_imp_plot(model,X_train):
    feature_names = list(X_train.columns)
    importances = model.feature_importances_
    indices = np.argsort(importances)
    plt.figure(figsize=(15,15))
    plt.title('Feature Importances')
    plt.barh(range(len(indices)), importances[indices], color ="red", align="center")
    plt.yticks(range(len(indices)), [feature_names[i] for i in indices])
    plt.xlabel("Relative importance")
    plt.show()

In [66]:
post_pruned_trees = []

#For each alpha value prune the tree and store in a list
for value in ccp_alphas:
    tree = DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state = 1, ccp_alpha=value)
    tree.fit(X_train, y_train)
    post_pruned_trees.append(tree)

    
#Evaluate the pruned trees
recall_train = []
recall_test = []

for value in post_pruned_trees:
    y_pred_train = value.predict(X_train)
    values_train = recall_score(y_train, y_pred_train)
    recall_train.append(values_train)

for value in post_pruned_trees:
    y_pred_test = value.predict(X_test)
    values_test = recall_score(y_test,y_pred_test)
    recall_test.append(values_test)


#Accuracy of train and test scores
train_scores = [value.score(X_train, y_train) for value in post_pruned_trees]
test_scores = [value.score(X_test, y_test) for value in post_pruned_trees]
    
index_best_model = np.argmax(recall_test)
best_model = post_pruned_trees[index_best_model]
print("Best model is : ",index_best_model)
print("Recall value giving best pred model is : ",recall_test[index_best_model])
print("Best alpha value is : ",ccp_alphas[index_best_model])

Observations and Buisiness Recommendations¶

  1. The best performing model was derived from Decision Tree Modelling with post pruned tree where Recall values are a lot similar.

  2. The customer attributes more significant are :

    a. Income - Higher the Income, more chances the customer will accept a personal loan. b. Family - As familly size grows, customers are more willing to accept personal loan c. Education_2 - Customers with Education level 2 are more willing to accept a personal loan than levels 1 & 3 d. Education_3 - Customers with Education level are more willing to accept a personal loan than level 1 e. CCAvg - As the monthly spending of customers increase, the more they are willing to accept personal loan

  3. Focus more on customers who fall into the categories as mentioned above.

  4. Bank can focus on improving campaigns for Online users as they are very much less.

  5. Can focus more on existing cutomers like the ones with Securities accound and CD account by giving them special discounts compared to searching for new customers.

  6. Improve customer services and offers for varied age group people.

  7. Simplify the loan procedures to ease the process.
